steven,

First of all, even papered pieces may have stuff that might need to be 
taken care of on
them (red rust, etc.), and I&#39;d guess even some of these end up getting 
&quot;primped&quot;
by later owners.  Sorry - Papers are a good start, but...

I had alluded to Jim&#39;s article about tsuba care - he recommends boiling 
water, which works
pretty well.

On paint, I should have been more clear (that&#39;s what I get for typing 
late at night) - often older
tsubas were lacquered - remmnants of old paint on a tsuba should be 
handled with the greatest
care/respect (on really old tsuba you&#39;ll see the paint form this 
funky/cool amalgum with the surface
patina) - you have to proceed carefully (or just leave well enough 
alone) when you have old
paint like that - I had a tosho once I nicknamed &quot;rusty crusty&quot; because 
there was a fairly thick
uncared for patina on it - BUT there was also a fair amount of what 
appeared to be original
lacquer, so I left it well enough alone - while the tsuba would probably 
have looked a whole
lot better/sold for more if I had just attacked it a little with the 
ivory/rubbing, it didn&#39;t seem
right since it would have nuked the lacquer as well...  The real answer 
is experience...  You need
to go and look at and study (and take good pictures of if you&#39;re 
motivated) a bunch of good tsuba...

On &quot;primped&quot; tsuba, an amazing number of tsuba in the US appear to have 
gotten the &quot;treatment&quot; -
I&#39;ve pretty much stopped buying pieces from people in the US who I don&#39;t 
know because of this -
I&#39;ve been burned enough so I can usually recognize its been jacked with, 
but I get tired of sending
pieces back - but you&#39;ll even get stuff from Japan occasionally that has 
been &quot;helped&quot;...  (comments
about how many people don&#39;t seem to understand white balance on digital 
cameras deleted).

Gotta run,

rkg
